    {
      "id": "UZr3FPW8TWkmTTPgRt3Ix",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 454,
      "y": 481.5,
      "width": 1043.7392578125,
      "height": 950,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "aD",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 870775913,
      "version": 1574,
      "versionNonce": 945232209,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1781331984064,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "1. Which DB?\nSQL or NOSQL\nSQL : Postgres, mySQL, DB2 etc\nNoSQL : \n  a. Key value store : Redis, Amazon Amazon DynamoDB\n  b. column store: Casandra, BigTable\n  c. document db: MongoDB, couchDB\n  c. graph db: Neo4j\n\n2. Replication?\n  a. Single leader : master slave\n    Best for read heavy systems\n    Ex : Postgres replication, mySQL replication\n    Problems : replication lag, read your writes, monotonic reads, prefix reads\n  b. Multi leader : \n    Best for multi region applications or collaborative users\n    EX : CouchDb, ActiveMQ\n    Problems : Same as above and write conflicts ( needs conflict resolution like last write wins)\n  c. Leaderless\n    Best for high availability systems, globally distributed applications\n    Ex : cassandra, dynamoDB\n    Problems : split brain, read repairs ( stale replca must be repaired during reads), Quorums and concensus\n\n3. Sharding : Partitioning data\noptions to scale DB?\nScaleup db or scale out, \nsharding is scale out\nA to M and N to Z in 2 servers\nStrategies: \n  a. Hash based ( key % n)\n  b. Key range ( A to M and N to Z)\n  c. directory based ( a service that maps keys to shards)\nProblems:\n  a. Hotspot or celebrity key problem ( uneven traffic)\n  b. rebalancing when nodes get added/ removed ( soln : consistent hashing)\n  c. cross shard joins and transactions are hard\n   \n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "1. Which DB?\nSQL or NOSQL\nSQL : Postgres, mySQL, DB2 etc\nNoSQL : \n  a. Key value store : Redis, Amazon Amazon DynamoDB\n  b. column store: Casandra, BigTable\n  c. document db: MongoDB, couchDB\n  c. graph db: Neo4j\n\n2. Replication?\n  a. Single leader : master slave\n    Best for read heavy systems\n    Ex : Postgres replication, mySQL replication\n    Problems : replication lag, read your writes, monotonic reads, prefix reads\n  b. Multi leader : \n    Best for multi region applications or collaborative users\n    EX : CouchDb, ActiveMQ\n    Problems : Same as above and write conflicts ( needs conflict resolution like last write wins)\n  c. Leaderless\n    Best for high availability systems, globally distributed applications\n    Ex : cassandra, dynamoDB\n    Problems : split brain, read repairs ( stale replca must be repaired during reads), Quorums and concensus\n\n3. Sharding : Partitioning data\noptions to scale DB?\nScaleup db or scale out, \nsharding is scale out\nA to M and N to Z in 2 servers\nStrategies: \n  a. Hash based ( key % n)\n  b. Key range ( A to M and N to Z)\n  c. directory based ( a service that maps keys to shards)\nProblems:\n  a. Hotspot or celebrity key problem ( uneven traffic)\n  b. rebalancing when nodes get added/ removed ( soln : consistent hashing)\n  c. cross shard joins and transactions are hard\n   \n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
